    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1970-05-25T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1970-05-25T00:00:00-05:00" n="365"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d365">
                <head>365. Memorandum From Secretary of Commerce <persName corresp="#p_SMH3"
                        type="from">Stans</persName> to President <persName type="to"
                        >Nixon</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d365fn1">Source: National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Subject
                        Files, Box 339, <gloss target="#t_HAK1">HAK</gloss>/<persName
                            corresp="#p_REL1">Richardson</persName> Meetings, April–May 1970. No
                        classification marking. Printed from a copy sent to <persName
                            corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName>.</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1970-05-25">May 25, 1970</date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>Following on our several discussions about the commercial attachés of the State
                    Department, I prepared a memorandum a short time ago outlining a proposal
                    whereby these individuals might be transferred to the Department of
                        Commerce.<note n="2" xml:id="d365fn2">
                        <ref target="#d362">Document 362</ref>.</note> I sent a draft copy of that
                    memorandum to Bill Rogers, but did not send one to you.</p>
                <p>Bill’s people misconstrued the situation and assumed that I had sent the
                    memorandum to you, with the result that you have now received a reply to a
                    document that you did not receive in the first place.</p>
                <pb facs="0825" n="794" xml:id="pg_794"/>
                <p>I have since talked to Bill about this and suggested that instead of arguing this
                    matter by correspondence, he and I sit down with three or four of our key people
                    and try to work out a solution that will provide more effective commercial
                    assistance overseas in our export and foreign investment programs.</p>
                <p>He has agreed to this, so that there is nothing that you need do at this time,
                    and I hope that we can work something out without troubling you further.<note
                        n="3" xml:id="d365fn3">In a May 28 memorandum <persName>Kennedy</persName>
                        informed <persName corresp="#p_KHA1">Kissinger</persName> of <persName
                            corresp="#p_SMH3">Stans</persName>’ agreement with <persName
                            corresp="#p_RWP1">Rogers</persName> and that “<persName
                            corresp="#p_BCF1">Bergsten</persName> feels this is not a White House
                        matter and advises that you not raise it with Under Secretary <persName
                            corresp="#p_REL1">Richardson</persName>.” (National Archives, Nixon
                        Presidential Materials, <gloss target="#t_NSC1">NSC</gloss> Files, Subject
                        Files, Box 339, <gloss target="#t_HAK1">HAK</gloss>/<persName
                            corresp="#p_REL1">Richardson</persName> Meetings, April–May 1970)</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <persName corresp="#p_SMH3">Maurice H. Stans</persName>
                        <note n="4" xml:id="d365fn4">Printed from a copy that bears this typed
                            signature.</note>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
